    "prompt": "Left corner is denied. 7 on the clock. What now?",
    "choices": [
      {
        "id": "c1",
        "label": "Rip baseline and back-cut behind him to the rim.",
        "quality": "best",
        "feedback_text": "Best read. Hand in the lane means the rim is open. You beat x4 to the front of the basket before the clock could decide.",
        "order": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "c2",
        "label": "V-cut up to the wing for a relief catch.",
        "quality": "acceptable",
        "feedback_text": "Okay. The relief catch keeps the play alive, but the corner denial was the layup window you just spent the clock on.",
        "partial_feedback_text": "Relief keeps the possession — and trades the rim for the clock. Back-cut next time.",
        "order": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "c3",
        "label": "Stand in the corner and call for it.",
        "quality": "wrong",
        "feedback_text": "Not yet. His hand is already in the lane. Standing still hands him the deflection.",
        "order": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "c4",
        "label": "Front-cut up into the paint.",
        "quality": "wrong",
        "feedback_text": "Not yet. Front cuts let him stay attached and x4 steps up — the cut dies before it reaches the rim.",
        "order": 4
      }
    ],
    "best_read": "Rip your outside foot baseline and back-cut hard behind x2 to the front of the rim. The passer leads you to the layup before x4 rotates up; the shot clock buys the window the swing pass would have wasted.",
    "acceptable_reads": [
      "V-cut up to the wing relief — keeps the play alive, but the clock decides on the next bounce."
    ],
    "bad_reads": [
      "Stand in the corner and call for it — x2's hand deflects the entry.",
      "Front-cut into the paint — x4 steps up and the cut dies at the rim."
    ],
    "common_miss_reason": "Players hold the corner spot waiting for the swing because the C&S is the natural finish on a swing-rotation. With the clock under 8, the defender knows the swing is coming and pre-commits to the lane. The cutter has to read that pre-commit and punish it before the clock decides for them.",
    "why_best_read_works": "The denying defender's hand-in-lane stance is closed off to the rim. A baseline back-cut puts the cutter behind the help-side rotation before x4 can rotate up; the lead pass lands at the rim with the shot clock buying the window.",
    "decoder_teaching_point": "Late clock + denial = baseline backdoor. The corner is the only catch the defense can't recover to.",
    "lesson_connection": "backdoor-window",
    "explanation_md": "**Late-Clock Backdoor — other side.** A corner denial works the same on the left as the right. x2's hand is in the lane and his hips are closed off from the rim — he's guarding the swing pass, not the basket. With 7 on the clock the defense knows the swing is coming and pre-commits to it. The only catch they can't recover to is the one behind them. **Rip baseline. Plant. Cut hard. Show your hands at the rim.**",
    "feedback": {
      "correct": "Right read. Same corner denial, left side. You beat x4's rotation before the clock decided.",
      "partial": "V-cut keeps the play alive, but you spent half the clock to do it. The corner denial was the layup window.",
      "wrong": "Read his body, not your spot. Hand in the lane = the rim is open behind him."
    },
    "self_review_checklist": [
      "Did I see x2's hand cutting off the corner pass?",
      "Did I rip the outside foot baseline before I committed?",
      "Did I cut hard, like I wanted the layup?",
      "Did I beat x4's rotation up from the nail?"
    ],
